Furthermore, the morphologies of N,S-CDs@SiO2, N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs and N,S-CDs@SiO2@NIPs were characterized using TEM and SEM. As shown in Fig. 3
                        , the TEM image of N,S-CDs@SiO2 revealed a spherical shape with uniform distribution, and the particle size was greater than that of N,S-CDs. And both N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs and N,S-CDs@SiO2@NIPs were also approximate spherical particles and had a larger size compared to N,S-CDs@SiO2 (Fig. 4
                        ).The above-mentioned results indicated that our nanomaterials had been successfully encapsulated by thee imprinting layers.

The sensitivity of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs and N,S-CDs@SiO2@NIPs for 4-hydroxybenzoic acid detection was explored. As shown in Fig. 12
                           a, at the same concentration of 4-hydroxybenzoic acid (0–100 μmol/L), the intensity of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs decreased distinctly compared to N,S-CDs@SiO2@NIPs, might be due to more binding sites of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs. The liner equations of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs and N,S-CDs@SiO2@NIPs were (F0-F)/F0 = 0.00213[4-hydroxybenzoic acid]+0.01895 (R2 = 0.9935) and (F0-F)/F0 = 0.00066[4-hydroxybenzoic acid]-0.000382 (R2 = 0.9991), respectively. And the limit of detection (LOD) of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs was 1.27 μmol/L (3σ/k). The imprinting factor (IF) is defined as the ratio of kMIPs to kNIPs, and used to evaluate the specific recognition ability of imprinted polymer. Furthermore, the IF value of our MIPs was 3.23, which illustrated that the prepared sensor exhibited good specific recognition ability for 4-hydroxybenzoic acid. Additionally, the sensitivity of N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs was further studied using Stern-Volmer model (Fig. 13
                           ), the Stern–Volmer plots for N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs- 4-hydroxybenzoic acid were calculated. F0/F and 4-hydroxybenzoic acid concentrations had a good linear correlation, and the Ksv was 0.0028 L μmol−1, which explained N,S-CDs@SiO2@MIPs had high sensitivity.
